Getting Started with the Salesforce Platform

https://trailhead.salesforce.com

Quick introduction

Salesforce is a powerful CRM platform that comes with a lot of standard functionality that a normal CRM would offer. However the special thing is that with the Salesforce platform, we can customize and build whatever it is that makes our company unique.

Terminologies

  • Database: In the context of Salesforce, a database is a giant spreadsheet.
  • An app is a set of objects, fields, and other functionality that supports a business process. We can switch between apps using the App Launcher.
  • Objects are tables in SF Database that store a particular kind of information. Standard Objects include Accounts, Contacts. Custom Objects are like Property, which can be used in the context of a real estate company.
  • Records are rows in object db tables.
  • Fields are columns in object db tables.

Salesforce Platform & Customization

We can develop custom obejcts and functionality specific to our business in SF Platform without writing code. This is called declarative development.

With declarative development, we use forms and drag-and-drop tools to customize tasks. We can also use programmatic development which uses things like Lightning components, Apex code and Visualforce pages.

  • Example: How to create a custom field to a standard object
    1. Click gear icon to launch Setup.
    2. Object Manager
    3. Contact
    4. Fields & Relationships >> New
    5. Select the data type
    6. Enter Field Label (Field Name is used for API & Reference Builder | Field Label is the Label).
      • You can also set field permission.
      • You can also add the field to specific layout
    7. Next & Save
  • Example: Custom Object - Chatter feed tracking


    Chatter feed tracking provides a way for multiple people to comment and collaborate on a particular record.

    The discussions and decisions are stored on the record so everyone can stay up to date on important decisions.

    Chatter feed eliminates the need for multiple email conversations about the same case/ topic.

    This is an example of "high impact, low effort".

The Setup Page

As a Salesforce administrator, we'll spend a lot of time in Setup. It is a one-stop shop for customizing, configuring and supporting the organization.


  1. Object Manager: Where we can view and customize standard and custom object.
  2. Setup Menu: Quick links to collection of pages that let us do everything from managing users to modifying security settings. In the Setup Menu, there are three main categories:
    • Administration: Where we manage user and data and email templates. Things like permission, add user..etc.
    • Platform Tools: This is where most of the customization happens. This is where we can view and manage data model, create apps, modify user interface and deploy new features. This is also where we deploy code.
    • Settings: Where we manage org information and security. Things like add business hours, change locale, and view org history.
  3. Main Window: Where things are displayed.

There is also a Quick Find box to search for settings and configurations in case we don't know where they are.

AppExchange

Salesforce is an enterprise ecosystem. There is a community of partners that use the flexibility of the SF platform to build amazing apps and other solutions that anyone can use.

AppExchange is like an App Store.


  • Strategy

    The AppExchange offer endless exciting opportunities. However before we start downloading we need to develop a strategy to get the highest value apps without duplicating functionality or make unnecessary investments.

    Follow these steps to develop a good AppExchange strategy:

    1. Identify departments that use or plan to use Saleforce. These are the primary stakeholder.
    2. Identify the stakeholder requirements and research what's available on AppExchange that best meets these. We would also need to discuss with department heads about business cases and needs. Some good questions to ask during the discussion follows. These are the questions to help identify apps that are best fit for each business case.
      • What business problem are we trying to solve?
      • What are the main pain points right now?
      • How many users need this app?
      • What's the budget?
      • What's the timeline?
    3. When we find an app that meets our need, it is good practice to first install that in a sandbox or Dev Ed environment. This is to ensure that this app doesn't interfere with any other previously installed apps.
    4. Take time to do evaluation and testing. Determine feature gaps or unwanted functionality. If necessary, invite the stakeholders to demo the apps and seek feedback.
    5. App is ready for prod! Make sure to provide relevant training and documentation.
  • After App has been installed

    Apps are installed using a package. The package is located in Setup / Installed Packages.

    We need to also click View Components to see more information about the package including custom fields, custom objects and Apex classes in the package. This information helps us determine whether we have any conflicts in our company.

Salesforce Architecture

What is so special about Salesforce? Well it starts with the architecture.

SF architecture is like a series of layers that sit on top of each other.


Important points to remember about SF architecture

  • SF is a cloud company. Everything is in the cloud.
  • SF Platform is the foundation of the services. It's made up by metadata, AI and robust APIs.
  • All the apps sit on top of the platform. Sales Cloud, Marketing Cloud are examples of apps.
  • Everything is integrated.

TRUST - Why trust the cloud?

https://trust.salesforce.com/en/ can be used to access real-time information on system performance and security.

SF's responsibility is to keep data and functionality safe.

Multitenant Cloud - Sharing is Caring

SF is set up like an apartment building where our company's own space is like a small apartment in a multilevel complex.

This idea is multitenancy. It simply means that we are sharing resources. No matter the size of the business, we get access to the same computing power, data storage and core features.

Trust and multitenancy go hand in hand. Also, since SF is a cloud service, we never have to worry about hardware. All is possible because of multitenancy.


Metadata - The Magic

Metadata is data about data.

Metadata is like the structure of our SF org.

For example, in the case of an object Property. The data about properties are like 'Boston', '$500,000' and '3 bedrooms'. Strip away all these metadata and we are left with only the Property object with all the fields.

APIs


Fundamentally, APIs allow different pieces of software to connect to each other and exchange information. It's like when two pieces of software have a contract to allow connection between them.

In SF, whenever we add a custom object or field, the platform automatically creates an API name (Field Name) that serves as an access point between our org and the database. The API is used to retrieve the metadata and data.

For example, we have a Contact object with a Name field. This field can be used in a bunch of places like the SF mobile app, a custom page or even an email template.


Apply .NET Skills to Salesforce

Database & .NET Basics

Move from SQL to SOQL

  • Objects

    In SQL Server, data is stored in tables and rows. The database in Force.com platform on the other hand uses objects to store data. Objects contain all the functionality we'd expect in a table with additional enhancements.

    Each objects comprises a number of fields, similarly to columns in a database table. Data is stored in records of objects which are like rows in database tables.

    There are two types of objects.

    STANDARD OBJECT CUSTOM OBJECTS
    Comes out-of-the box with SF New objects that we create to store information unique and
    e.g Accounts, Contacts,.. relevant to our application / org.
      For example, Orders or Invoices if we are working on an app
      to track inventory.

    Objects have relationship fields that define how records in an object relates to records in another objects. These are pretty much like primary and foreign key but they are more flexible, making it easier to design and implement data model.

    Another special things about objects is that they not only provide structure for storing data but also power the interface elements that allow users to interact with the data, such as tabs, the layout fields on a page and lists of related records. Objects have built-in support for features such as access management, validation, formulas and history tracking. All attributes of objects also have metadata about them.

  • SOQL Introduction

    SOQL is Salesforce Object Query Language. It is the language that is used to query data in Salesforce Objects (sObjects)

    SOQL is also a query language similarly to SQL. However SOQL is only used to perform queries with SELECT.

    SOQL has no equivalent INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE statements.

    Data manipulation in SF is handled using DML methods (data manipulation language).

    Another different is that SOQL has no such thing as SELECT *. This is because SF data lives in a multi-tenanted environment where everyone is sharing the database.

    In SOQL we specify each field name to return. Beyond this, SOQL is similar to SQL. However SOQL does not support advanced features that SQL SELECT does.

    In the SOQL Interface, we can choose either to type the SOQL query or hold down the CTRL key and select the Fields on the list.


    SOQL has only two required clauses: SELECT and FROM. The WHERE clause is optional.

    Note: Using wildcards especially leading and trailing wildcards such as illustrated in the above example isn't considered good practice.

    Note 2: In the above example, there are two fields AccountID and ID. In this example AccountID is associated with the Account record that this particular Contact was assigned to. In SQL language this is the Foreign Key relationship. The ID field is related to the contact, which in SQL language represents the Primary Key.

    • Joining tables in SOQL

      Joining objects in SOQL is not possible because apparently that's a good thing.

      While we’re bringing up foreign key relationships, you might now be wondering how you join tables in SOQL. The short answer is you don’t. SOQL has no equivalent JOIN clause. But don’t worry, because we think that’s a good thing.

      … However, in order to combine tables, instead of using the JOIN clause, in SF we write relationship queries.

      There are two types of relationship query:

      • Child-to-parent
      • Parent-to-children

      In the above screenshotted example, the relationship between Account and Contact is that Account is the parent and Contact is the child.

      • Child-to-Parent Query

        The SOQL relationship query uses "dot notation" to access data from the parent. That is..

        SELECT childfield1, childfield2, childfield3. Parent.parentField From Child

        One super important thing to note is that this type of query can traverse five levels up with the dot notation i.e we can go from child object to its parent, to the grand parent, to the great grand parent and so on.

        For example, the relationship between the Contact and Account object is that Contact is the child. The relationship between Account and Contact would be one to many.

        For this type of relationship, not all contacts are related to an account | not all accounts have a contact.

        Let's say, now we want to query all records in the Contact Object.

        In SOQL we would use this query:
        (pull everything from contact, show account.name if any)

        SELECT FirstName, LastName, Account.Name FROM CONTACT

        For this scenario (one-to-many), if we were using SQL we would need to use a RIGHT JOIN like..

        SELECT c.FirstName
          ,c.LastName
          ,a.Name
FROM Account a
RIGHT JOIN Contact C
                ON c.AccountID = a.ID

        So SOQL is somewhat simpler if we get the hang of it…

      • Parent-to-Child Query

        Parent-to-Child queries also use relationship name however the syntax is somewhat like a nested SELECT query.

        Let's say we want to write a query from the parent Account object and also returns information about each associated Contact.
        (Reminder: Account-Contact is One-to-many.)

        SELECT Name, (SELECT FirstName, LastName FROM Contacts) FROM Account

        ( The equivalent of this in SQL would be..

        SELECT a.Name
          ,c.FirstName
      ,c.LastName
FROM Account a
LEFT JOIN Contact c ON a.ID = c.AccountID
        • IMPORTANT NOTE

          Note that within the nested query, we used the plural Contacts, as opposed to Contact. This is important and also the part that trips people up.

          When working with relationship queries, the Parent-to-Child relationship name must be a Plural.

          When working with custom objects, the relationship is not only plural but it is appended with two underscores and an r.

          For example, the relationship name for the custom object My_Object__c is My_Objects__r.

    • Aggregates

      SOQL has aggregates. The big thing to be aware of when working with aggregate is that for most functions, the result that is returned is of AggregrateResult data type.
      (Official Doc)

      Functions Description
      AVG() Returns average value.
      COUNT() and COUNT(fieldName) and COUNT_DISTINCT() Returns number of rows matching query criteria.
      MIN() Returns the minimum value of a field.
      MAX() Returns the maximum value of a field.
      SUM() Returns the total sum of a numeric field.
      • Handling returned data from SOQL

        In Developer Console, Debug > Open Execute Anonymous Window. We can then type Apex code in then select Execute with Debug Only selected to only show debug information.

        List<AggregateResult> results = 
    [SELECT Industry, count(ID) total
     FROM Account Group BY Industry];
for (AggregateResult ar : results)
{
    System.debug('Industry: ' + ar.get('Industry'));
    System.debug('Total Accounts: ' + ar.get('total'))
;}


        Note:

        • total is an alias of count(ID). In SOQL, we can only alias fields in aggregate queries that use GROUP BY clause.

        Looking at that code block I think it does these:

        1. Query a table with two columns Industry and Count of Account with this Industry value. This table is alised with results. Not sure why the <AggregateResult> bit is there but it probably has something to do with the data type of this table.
        2. For ar in results: (ar is each row/ record)
          • print in debug (String 'industry' + the value in field Industry of each row)
          • _'Total Account' __total____
    • GROUP BY

      In addition to GROUP BY, SOQL offers other grouping clauses such as GROUP BY ROLLUP, GROUP BY CUBE and GROUPING. These clauses are useful when inspecting results that have been queried from several related tables.

      GROUP BY CUBE lets you add subtotal for all combinations of a grouped field in teh query results.

      Aggregate functions also supports HAVING which is similar to to SQL.

      (More about GROUP BY: doc)
      (More about HAVING: doc)

    • How to open the Developer Console

      The use of Developer Console is limited to user with the relevant permissions.

      List of User Permissions required are:

      • API Enabled
      • View All Data
      • Author Apex
      • Customize Application

      In SF Classic:

      In Lightning Experience:

    • Datetime

      The Datetime fields in SF are as PITA to work with as in SQL. However in SF there are several date functions.

      The full list of functions can be found here https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.soql_sosl.meta/soql_sosl/sforce_api_calls_soql_select_date_functions.htm.

      For example, we can group or filter data by date periods such as day, calendar month or fiscal year.

      SELECT CALENDAR_YEAR(CreatedDate),
           SUM(Amount)
FROM   Opportunity
GROUP BY CALENDAR_YEAR(CreatedDate)

Write SOSL Querie

  • What is SOSL

    SOQL is the langauge used to query data in sObjects. SOSL is the language that is used to perform text-based queries across multiple sObjects. It is Salesforce Object Search Language.

    SOSL is similar to MS FTS or Lucene.Net.

    Salesforce uses the open-source search and indexing engine Lucene to power SOSL, however it has been set up so that we don't have to worry about installing and configuring anything. We are not responsibile for maintaining indexes. This is a good and bad thing because for the most parts we don't have much control over how search indexes are used. However it also means writing SOSL queries is easy.

    Note: SOSL uses nickname search. It applies to English-language searches on Account, Contact, Lead and User object. E.g 'Joey' = 'Joseph'.

    Note: SOSL indexing is done asynchronously so it's possible to make a change to the system and not see the results in our SOSL search immediately.

  • Building SOSL Query

    (doc for all clauses)

    A basic SOSL query looks like the following:

    FIND {"grand*"} IN ALL FIELDS RETURNING Account(Name), Contact(LastName, FirstName, Email)

    Meaning:
    Step 1. Search through these objects: Account, Contact with the following search text: grand*.
    Step 2. Return Account.Name and Contact.LastName, FirstName, Email.

    • The FIND clause with search term

      This is a required clause. FIND is followed by whatever search term we are looking for, whether it's a single word or a phrase. In the above example it is the word 'grand'. We can also include wildcard character, e.g * (any character) or ? (only one character).

      However it has to be noted that although wildcards can be used in both the middle and the end of a search term, we should not do it because it impact query performance.

    • The IN clause

      (doc)
      This is used to specify a search group. It tells SF which fields to search.

      In the above example we specified ALL FIELDS. Although this gives the impresion that all fields will be searched, only certain text-based fields are included (these are email, name, phone, sidebar). This is dependent on the object which we specify in the RETURNING clause. The ALL FIELD is also the default setting if IN clause is not specified.

      The syntax is IN /SeachGroup/ where SearchGroup can be ALL FIELDS, EMAIL FIELDS, NAME FIELDS, PHONE FIELDS and SIDEBAR FIELDS. Numeric fields are not searchable.

      The IN clause does not apply to articles, documents, feed comments, feed items, files, products and solutions Objects. If these objects are specified in the RETURNING clause, the search is not limited to specific fields and all fields are searched.

    • The RETUNING clause

      This clause is used to specify which data to return and which object to search. In the above example we return the Name field from Account and three fields from Contact. The search looked through all searchable fields on both objects but returns only the included fields in the parenthesis.

      If we specify and object name without a field name in the parenthesis, the search only returns the ID for that object if a match is found.

    • Example 2 - Using nickname
      FIND {joey} IN ALL FIELDS RETURNING Account(Name), Contact(LastName, FirstName), Document(Name)

      Meaning:

      1. The search text is joey - This is a No description for this link for Joseph.
      2. Seach through these objects: Account, Contact, Document
      3. Return these: Account(Name), Contact(LastName) and Contact(FirstName), Document(Name)

SOSL or SOQL?

It depends on what we are trying to accomplish but the summary is:

SOQL For known object or related objects with known criteria
SOSL For things we don't know exact fields and (unrelated) objects

SOQL should be used if we need data from a single object and we know specifically the criteria for that object. SOQL is also the language we mostly use.

SOSL is most useful when we don't know the exact fields and objects that our data resides in and we need to search across multiple objects. This is also especially true when the objects aren't related because SOQL only works with related objects.

Writing efficient Queries

  • Intro

    Writing efficient queries does not simply mean better performance but also to ensure that we don't run into problem with the governore limits. As SF is a multi-tenanted platform, everyone has to share space. Governor limits are like resource referee. They ensure that everyone is playing by the rules and receives and equal share of the resource pie.

  • Query Optimizer

    SF's backend database uses Oracle but Force.com uses its own version of a Query Optimizer to evaluate cost-based queries. Similarly to most of the other ones, SF db optimizers relies on statistics gathered about the data. Most statistics are gathered weekly but the system also generates pre-queries that are cached every hour.

    The Query Optimizer evaluates SOQL queries and SOSL searches. It's like a traffic cop working by routing queries to the appropriate indexes. The QO looks at every incoming query and assigns a cost value for each potential query path that it identifies. It then uses these costs to determine which execution plan to use.

    The way that QO works is quite complicated.

  • Best practices

    (Salesforce effective query cheatsheet: doc)

    1. Building Selective Queries

    Apply filters using WHERE, and even AND | OR. Remember, having more WHERE is a good thing. The less data our query returns, the better.

    One important thing to note is that not all fields are created equally. Some fields, when included in the WHERE clause, make the query super-duper fast. These can be regarded as "super" field.

    The thing that makes these super field super are indexes.

    Some fields are automatically flagged to be indexes in standard as well as custom tables (sObjects). Here is the list:

    Indexed Fields Description
    ID Unique 18-char field that is sytem generated. This is the PK.
    Name Text-based field.
    OwnerID Reference to the owner of the object.
    CreatedDate Date & Time when record was created.
    SystemModStamp Read-only field that contains when the data was last updated.
      NOTE: This field is indexed where as LastModifiedDate (similar) is not.(More)
    RecordType ID of RecordType. RecordTypes are used to offer different UI results to users
    Master-Detail Fields FK used to indicate master-detail relationship
    Lookup Fields FK used to indicate a lookup relationship
    Unique Fields Custom fields can be marked as unique when they are created. These are
      automatically indexed. (If they are unique I guess they are like IDs..)
    External ID Fields External ID Fields are like Unique Fields that are foreign. Used for integration
      purposes

    NOTE: It's possible for a SF customer to request a custom index from SF Support by creating a case and including SOQL with the indexed field.

    (More about Building Selective Query: doc)

    1. Index Selectivity Exceptions

    Using an indexed field doesn't always make the query golden. There are things that we do in queries that make them non-selective and prone to full table scan. Avoid these things:

    • Querying for null rows: SELECT ID, Name FROM Account WHERE Custom_field__c = null.
    • Negative filter operators: SELECT CaseNumber FROM Case WHERE Status != 'New' (Similar for NOT LIKE, EXCLUDE.
    • Leading wildcards: SELECT ID, LastName, FirstName FROM Contact WHERE LastName LIKE '%smi%'.
    • Text fields with comparison operators: SELECT AccountID, Amount FROM Opportunity WHERE Order_Number__c > 10. Using comparison operators >, <, >=, <= with text-based fields is bad practice.
    1. Query Plan Tool

    In the Developer Console, the useful tool Query Plan is not enabled by default.


    It's quite good.

    When we evaluate a poorly performing query, the Query Plan displays a table that lists the cost of the query and that it will be doing a TableScan << this is not a good thing.


    The Query Plan can also help us by indicate that an index can be used.


    (More about Query Plan: doc)

    • More - non-deterministic formula fields

      Strive to avoid creating queries with non-deterministic formula fields. Formula fields are custome dynamic fields that are calculated at runtime. These are popular and tend to be overused.

      A formula field is considered non-deterministic when its value varies over time.

      (doc)

Modifying Records with DML

The Query Results pane displayed in the Developer Console not only displays the results but also functions as a query grid.

We can click in the result grid and use the buttons below the grid to insert, update or delete data.

  • DML

    Although SOQL is used to query data, DML handles the managing of data.

    Statements Description
    insert Inserts new record.
    update Updates an existing record.
    upsert This is a special op, it creates the record & update with a single statement.
      It uses a specified field to determine the existing objects or the ID field.
      if no field is specified.
    delete Deletes an existing record.
    undelete Restores one or more existing record from the recycle bin.
    merge Another special op. It can merge up to 3 records of the same object type into
      one of the records. The other records are deleted. Any related records are re-
      parented.
  • How to execute DML

    In Apex, there are two ways to execute DML statements.

    • Using the statement itself..
    Account acct = new Account(
	Name='Test Account',
	Phone='(255)555-8989');
insert acct;
    • Using database class methods. The advantage of doing this is that we have access to the allOrNone parameter to specify whether the operation can partially succeed. When this parameter is set to false, if the error occurs on a partial set of records, the successful records are committed. Errors for the failed records are returned. With the partial success option there are no exceptions. In the below example, the allOrNone parameter is set to false and return the sucess or failure info in an array.
    Account acct = new Account(
	Name='test Account',
	Phone-'(255)555-8989');
Database.SaveResult[] results = Database.insert(acct, false)

    By default, the allOrNone parameter is true which means that the Database method behaves exactly like its DML counterpart and throws an exception if a failure is encountered.

Developer Beginner

Platform Development Basics

The DreamHouse app

Throughout this Development module we are going to use the following scenario to explore the many tools and technologies that the SF plateform provides.

About the business:

You’re a developer for DreamHouse Realty, a company that aggregates real estate listings to better connect homebuyers and real estate agents. Your boss asks you to build a new system to track real estate listings. Your internal employees will use it to track and communicate about properties. Your partner real estate brokers will use it to access information about customers. And your customers will view properties and contact brokers for viewings.

Getting started with the Salesforce platform

At Salesforce, the servies are grouped by clouds. There's Sales Cloud for CRM, Service Cloud for customer support and handful of other clouds that helps different types of companies support different type of business activities and functions.

There is one thing that all these clouds share in common and that is the Salesforce platform.

SF Platform is a group of technologies that support development work of other technologies on top of it. It does not only support SF clouds but also all custom functionality that is built by customers and partners. The functionality can range from single page layouts to full-scale application.

Different type of platforms

The core plateform lets us develop custom data models and applications for both desktop and mobile.

The Heroku platform gives developer the power to build highly scalable web apps and back-end services using Python, Ruby, Go and more. It also provides database tools that syncs with data from Salesforce.

The host of Salesforce APIs let developers integrate and connect all our enterprise data, networks and identity information.

The Mobile SDK is a suite of technologies that lets us build native, HTML5 and hybrid apps that have the same reliability and security as the Salesforce app.

Development without code

Salesforce is a metadata-driven platform. And here's how it works:

When we look at data in Salesforce, it is not a user interface sitting on top of a run-of-the-mill relational database. What we are looking at is actually an abstraction of the database that is driven by the platform's metadata-aware architecture.

In this abstraction, objects are database tables. Within these objects, the fields are columns and records are rows in the database.


The above image shows the detail page of an account record. The fields Type, Account Number, Website ..etc.. are the metadata that defines the structure of the app. The values are the actual data. The actual data is not important in term of data model.

This metadata-driven development models the special thing about Salesforce platform. Because the platform is metadata-aware, it can auto-generate a significant part of the user experience. Things like dialogs, record lists, detail views & forms which normally would need to be develope just come for free. We also get all the basic functionality like create, read, update and delete (CRUD) for custom object records in the database.

All this prebuilt functionality allows us more time to work on the more sophisticated custom features.

For the DreamHouse app, it is built using various parts of the Salesforce platform. The below diagram gives an overview of system landscape of the DreamHouse application set.


In the DreamHouse app, there are three custom objects that suppor the app's core functionality.

  • Brokers: information about partner broker
  • Properties: photos and information about properties that are on the market
  • Favorites: properties customers have favourited

In the Setup Menu, we can open the Schema Builder to see the data model. Like this:


On the Salesforce platform, developers are encouraged to minimize code. This is because the platform's metadata-driven architecture lets devs complete most basic development tasks without the need to write a line.

Salesforce offers a lot of tools for point-and-click or declarative development. Most of these tools require little to no understanding of development principles.

Some development tasks that are considered low code are writing validation rules or hooking up components with UI elements. These require basic programmatic knowledge to complete but are not very rigorous. For example, if we know something about logic, conditions and CRUD operations, we can do more with the Process Builder, like this:


Code with Salesforce Languages

(doc)

As a SF developer, there are three core programmatic technologies to learn about:

  • Lighting Component Framework: A UI development framework, similar to AngularJS or React.
  • Apex: Salesforce's proprietary programming language with Java-like syntax.
  • Visualforce: A markup language that lets us create custom Salesforce pages with code that looks a lot like HTML and optionally can use a powerful combination of Apex and Javascript.
  • Lightning Components

    This is a UI development framework for desktop and mobile. It's component-based approach to UI development which means we use prebuilt and custom Lightning components to quickly develop sleek and consistent UIs for our apps.

    As of Spring'19 release we can build Lightning components using two programming models:

    • Lightning Web Components model
    • (original) Aura Components model

    These two can co-exist and interoperate on a page.
    (Training here: Lightning Web Component Basics)

    Dive in by the following steps:

    1. Gear icon to open Setup Menu.
    2. Search for 'Lightning Components' or look under Custom Code > Lightning Components.
    3. Select a component then click Developer Console.

    Lightning components are mostly XML markup that contains Aura-specific and static HTML tags.

    Things to note about Lightning Components:

    • Client-side Javascript and server-side Apex controllers.
    • Mobile-ready

  • Visualforce

    Visualforce is similar to any other web development. It lets you create and customize pages in Salesforce as well as integrate with other standard web technologies including HTML, CSS and Javascript.

    The difference between Lightning components and Visualforce is that with LC, we are developing components that can be pieced together to make pages. With Visualforce, we are developing entire pages. LC is newer and better for mobile development. There are several situations where it's better to develope using Visualforce.

Extend the Salesforce platform - API

Things like Lightning App Builder and Process Builder have little interaction with SF's underlying APIs.

As we move towards a more programmatic development, we find a robust set of APIs that lets us access our SF's data in a variety of way.

Put simply, every object in our org has an API name that lets us access data for the object.

APIs can be used in Lightning components, Apex and Visualforce. One example is:

Property__c property = [SELECT Name, Price__c from Property__c WHERE Id=:propId];

The __c denotes that this is a custom object or field. This query is using the automatically created API access point for the custom Property object to retrieve information about properties using propID.

Here are the list of APIs that Salesforce provides and what they are used for:

API What we can do with it
SOAP API Integrate our org's data with other applications using SOAP protocol.
REST API Access objects in our org using standard REST protocol.
Metadata API Manage customizations in our org and build tools that manage our metadata model
Tooling API Build custom development tool for platform applications
Marketing Cloud API A combination of SOAP and REST. REST to expose Marketing Cloud capabilities.
  SOAP for providing comprehensive access to email functionality.
Bulk API Load, delete and perform asynchronous queries on large data sets
Streaming API Send and receive notifications securely and efficiently. Notifications can reflect
  data changes or custom events.
Chatter REST API Build API for Chatter, Communities, Recommendations, Files, Topic & more.
Mobile SDK It's technically a software development kit. Integrate Native or Hybrid mobile apps
  directly with Salesforce.

(More: doc)

Extend the Salesforce platform - Heroku

Heroku is all about interacting with outside world. It is a web development platform that lets us build quickly, deploy and scale web apps.

There is a lot of flexibility with Heroku. We can write code with Java, Python or PHP.

Heroku is built on Amazon Web Services so a lot of the infrastructure concerns are taken care of. Heroku Connect unifies our SF data with our Heroku Pstgres data so we don't have to manage moving information across two platforms. These means you don't have to worry too much about infrastructure or data storage.

Extend the Salesforce platform - IoT, Bots and more

  • IoT

    Depending on our industry, integrating SF with IoT may or may not be a necessity.

    Smart devices can be connected to smart devices i.e smart locks, light, thermostats..etc..

  • Bots

    Chatbots are typically used in external customer services. However we can also use chatbots for internal staff to navigate data e.g knowledge base..etc..

Data Modeling

Basic things about Objects

A data model is a way to model what database tables look like in a way that makes sense to humans.

However in Salesforce, things are a bit different..

Normal Database model Salesforce Notes
Tables Objects Standard objects, custom objects, external objects, platform events
    , BigObjects.
Columns Fields  
Rows Records  

Objects are container for information but they also gives us special functionality. For example when we create a custom object we can also design how it is displayed as a UI to user.

Every standard and custom objects has fields attached to it. The main types of Fields are Identity, System, Name, Custom. These four are standard on every object in Salesforce. Each standard object comes with a set of prebuilt standard fields. We can also add custom fields to standard objects.

Every field has a data type. SF supports a bunch of data type. i.e

  • Checkbox
  • Date | DateTime
  • Formula

Custom objects and custom fields are suffixed with __c.

Create Object Relationships

Object relationships are a special field type that connects two objects together.

For example, let's say we have a standard objects called Accounts and we are working for Sales company. If Sale rep opens an Account i.e creating an Account record, it is very likely that they have a few Contacts at that Account's company. Therefore we should create a relationship between the Account object and Contact object.

The Account-Contact relationship is one that comes out of the box with SF. However we can create custom relationships.

There are two types of Relationships.

  • Lookup Relationships

    The Account-Contact example is one of a lookup relationship. It's essentially a relationship that allows two objects to "look up" one another from the related items on the other object.

    Lookup relationships can be one-to-one or one-to-many. Account-Contact for example is one to many.

    Lookup relationships are casual.

    Lookup relationship is suitable when the objects are related in not all cases.

  • Master-Detail relationships

    In contrast to the casual counterpart that is the lookup relationship, Master-Detail are a bit tighter.

    In this relationship, one object is the master and the other one is the detail. The master controls certain behaviours of the detail object. For example: who can view data.

    An example of master-detail relationship would be Property-Offer where deleting the property deletes all of its associated offers from the system.

    In this type of relationship the detail object does not work as a standalone. It's highly dependent on the master.

  • the third one - hierarchical

    Hierarchical relationships are similar but special type of lookup relationships. The difference is that hierarchical relationships are only available for the User object. This can be used for things like creating organisation structure for employees.


Data Management

Import Data

We can easily import data into Salesforce in the form of .csv file. There are two main methods for importing data:

  • Data Import Wizard: accessible via the Setup menu, can import up to 50,000 records at a time. Simple interface and field mappings. Only allow import in common standard object.
  • Data Loader: this is a seperate client application that can import up to 5 million records at a time of any data type from files or from a database connection. It can be operated through user interface or the command line. With CLI we can specify data sources, field mappings and other parameters via configuration files. This makes thing easy to automate using API calls. This method should be used for scheduled import. It uses SOAP API to process records, however ew can configure it to use Bulk API instead. This way we can load a larger number of records simultaneously.

Export data

There are two methods for exporting data

DATA EXPORT WIZARD DATA LOADER
In-browser separate client application
Manual or auto export, weekly or monthly UI or CLI (CLI more powerful)

Data Security

  • Data security modeling and introduction

    Data security and permission is the important thing that we should think about after we have designed and implmented our data model.

    Although the security and permission can be set entirely using the UI, the security/ sharing model actually works at API level. Therefore any permissions that we specify apply even if we query or update the data via API calls.

    Configuration of levels of data access can be done at multiple levels i.e Organization, Objects, Fields and even Records.

    1. Organization

    Example: list of authorized users, password policies, limit login hours and location

    1. Objects

    This is quite simple. We set the permission on the particular type of object. Example: interviewers can view positions for job applications but cannot edit or delete.

    1. Fields

    Even if the user has access to the object we can also apply permission at the field level. For example we can let interviewers see position object without the salary field which is only visible to management and recruiter.

    1. Records

    Although the user can see an object, it doesn't mean that they should see all the records. i.e Person A should not be able to view (or edit) Person B records. Record permission can be configured in four different ways:

    • Organization-wide defaults specify the default level of access all useres have to each others' records. This is used to lock down our data to the most restrictive level because it is a baseline. Then we can use other record-level security and sharing tools to selective give more access to users.
    • Role hierarchies gives access for user with higher in the hierarchy to all records owned by users below them in the hierarchy. The role hierarchy doesn't have to match organizational chart exactly. In fact each role in the hierarchy should represent a level of data access that a user or a group of users needs.
    • Sharing rules are automatically exceptions to organization-wide defautls for particular groups of users, making them able to get to records they don't own or can't normally see. These are similar to role hierarchies in that they are both used to give more access to users i.e they cannot be stricter than org-wide rule.
    • Manual sharing is normally not automated like org-wide or role hierarchy however it can be useful in some situations i.e two users sharing inbetween themselves. A scenario where this has to be done is when a recruiter goes on a holiday and needs to temporarily hand over work to someone else.


    Note: We should start with a table of various types of users in our org. In the table specify the level of access to data that each type of users has for each object and for fields as well as record. We can then refer to this table when we set up our security model.

    The Audit System can be used to provide information for diagnosing potential security issues or when we have to work on real situations. This process should be done internally regularly to detect and avoid potential abuse.

  • Control Access to the Org

    Things like: password policy, when and where users can log in..

    Every SF user is identified by a username, a password and a single profile. There are settings on this user profile that determines what tasks user can perform, what data they see and what they can do with the data.

    A User Profile has a liences which determines which profiles are available for each user.

    We cannot delete a user but we can deactivate an account so they can't log in and access any records. An account can also be freezed which also prevents them from logging on to our org while we are working to deactivate them.

    There are a few Password Policies that we can configure to ensure users' passwords are strong and secure. We can even configure login attempts and lockout periods.

    We can also configure Whitelisted/ Trusted IP Ranges for our Org. On default when a user logs in from a non-cached IP address they will be asked to verify their identity typically by entering a verificaion code. This can be bypassed by allowing a certain range of trusted IP addresses. If configured, login from non-trusted IP addresses would just have to be verifified using a verification code.

    Restrict Login Access by IP Address Using Profiles: Setup > Profiles - allows us to restrict location for login access for certain users.

    We can also restrict login access by Time. This is also done via Setup > Profiles.
    (If a user is logged in when their login hours end, they can continue to view their current page however they cannot take any further action.)

Additional Note

Apex code snippet

While working on the trailhead lessons I noticed some Apex code snippets here and there. So I thought it'd be a good idea to copy them here to analyze the syntax.

Create New Account & Contact records

This was done by entering the following Apex code snippet into the Developer Console

// Add Account and related Contact
Account acct = new Account(
    Name='Test Account',
    Phone='(225)555-8989',
    NumberOfEmployees=10,
    BillingCity='Baton Rouge');
insert acct;
// Get the Id of the Inserted Account
ID acctID = acct.ID;
// Add a contact to the Account.
Contact con = new Contact(
    FirstName='Joseph',
    LastName='Smith',
    Phone='(225)555-8787',
    Email='jsmith@testaccount.com',
    AccountId=acctID);
insert con;

First of all, the following bits indicate that to declare a variable, you have to start by first calling the data type.
Account acct = ...
ID acctID = ....
Contact con = ...

This bit new Account() can be broken down like this:

  • new is a function to create new object record, it is followed by ..
  • calling the Object type (Account | Contact) like a method, with..
  • the object fields being declared in brackets, seperate by commas ,.

After we declare the variable as the new object record, we then use the insert function. Note that *we only need to do insert var because the variable itself has relation to the actual object type. Therefore to insert, we don't have to declare the object/ table name one more time.

We can also invoke properties of a variable e.g accID = acct.ID (ID attribute of variable acct). This is like calling out a class variable from an instance.

NOTE: Objects in apex are like Class. Object fields are like Class attributes.
